<Rate>5</Rate><Text>Two days ago, in the middle of the night, I was awakened to the sound of my cat howling in pain. I knew something was seriously wrong and took her to Animal Urgent Care of South OC. Due to covid restrictions, I had to wait in the car during the exam. After some time, the doctor called me and gave me the absolute worst news that my cat had a serious, untreatable illness and would not make it much longer.

The doctor gave me this news in a matter of fact, yet incredibly compassionate manner. She explained all the details so I could truly understand and, most importantly, reassured me that there was nothing I could have done + my cat wasn‚Äôt currently in pain because of the pain medication they gave her. I can‚Äôt tell you what a relief that was to my aching heart. She gave me space to decide what I was going to do, but in my mind, I knew the right thing to do was to put my cat down.

The doctor asked me whether I wanted to come in and say goodbye and whether I wanted to be present for my cat‚Äôs last moments. I really appreciated that she did not make any assumptions, which made me feel incredibly supported and respected.

When I went inside to say goodbye, they brought her into the room and reassured me that I could take as long as I needed. In the moment that the final medication was administered, the doctor was gentle and kind and I truly felt that, despite the pain of the moment, I was not alone.

My sweet little Jasmine cat died, peacefully, head cradled in my hands... and I could not have been more grateful for those last moments.

Again, the doctor reassured me that I could take as long as I needed. She also reassured me that the staff would treat her body with dignity. Nobody wants to say goodbye to their beloved pet, but I‚Äôm telling you, the amount of kindness, empathy, dignity, and compassion I received made it all bearable.

But here‚Äôs the thing... the moment of passing is NOTHING compared to the grief and sadness I currently feel. So you can imagine how much it meant to come home this evening and find a card in the mailbox.... Signed by all staff with personal, individual messages of condolence. And a little card with a Jasmine‚Äôs paw print.üò≠It sure doesn‚Äôt take the pain away, but I‚Äôll be damned if it didn‚Äôt make me feel a little less alone in the world.

I wish that Jasmine was still here, but my heart is at peace. I could not be more grateful for the work that they did, and for every ounce of kindness that was shown to me and to Jasmine in her final moments.

Thank you all for walking with me through one of the hardest moments of my life and thank you for taking care of Jasmine. I will forever think of you with incredible gratitude.<//Text>< Pictures>

<rating>5</rating>< review>
We had to take our new puppy to urgent care because our older/bigger dog attacked him. The redemption we got upon arriving was quick and very friendly. They took our pup inside immediately. After a few minutes they called me to get a more thorough account of what had happened. After the Dr. was able to see him they called with an update and a plan of care. Every step along the way the would call with an update and recommendation for what to do next. There was never any high pressure recommendations. They quoted us all prices up front and gave us the opportunity to choose the treatment we wanted. I bring this up because fur babies steal our hearts and it would be very easy to pay for something that maybe you could wait on. When they were done with everything the vet called, told us what care she had provided, what the plan at home would be and when to follow up with our regular vet. They gave us prescriptions for what she felt was appropriate to keep our puppy healthy and with minimal pain. This is the second time we have had to use this urgent care (different dog) with the same great experience.< /review>

That moment we all dread...  10PM and my 4 month old rottie puppy eats a SOCK!  I called Animal Urgent Care, and they calmed me down, and let me know it would be risky to let him try to pass it on his own.

So, I drove him on down to the team there.  He immediately took to them, they all thought he was great... I asked if they just wanted to keep him... they said no.

They were able to induce vomiting and get the sock, which they were going to give back === NOOOO THANK YOU!!   He's no worse for the wear, still wants to eat socks.

They got all this done very quickly (less than ~30 mins) while setup for and practicing social distancing.  Well Done, and THANK YOU Animal Urgent Care!!</text>

<Review>Over the years, we have had to bring a number of our senior rescue dogs to the Animal Urgent Care of South Orange County when they were having some emergency issues.  Most recently, we brought Chappy, our 14 1/2-year-old Westie, who we rescued in 2007.   Earlier in the evening, we noticed that he was having difficulty breathing which progressively got worse, so we got him to AUCSC.  We appreciated the friendliness compassion, and professionalism of the entire staff, particularly the candor of Dr. Laura Cross. The diagnosis of Westie lung disease (pulmonary fibrosis) and an enlarged heart was devastating to us.  The prognosis for a senior dog was not good.   If Chappy was younger, we might have attempted some of the treatment options.  We picked Chappy up around 7:30 A.M. and took him to our regular vet.  After seeing the stress he was under, we made the difficult decision to let him go.  This was the 16th time we had to walk down that road in the 46 years of our marriage.  It is never easy, but with Chappy, it was extremely hard to make, because he was such a happy dog who got along famously with many of the other rescues that we have had over the 13 years Chappy was with us

We are very thankful that the Animal Urgent Care of South Orange County is available for those emergencies that our beloved pets find themselves.  Each time we have had to bring one of our rescues to them, we have been impressed with personnel their services.  The only negative comment would be that their charges seem rather high.  What are you going to do?   You pay for it!</Review>< user_name>
James Rogers< /user_name>

<GmapID>0x80dcee896354092b:0x1569bc95125a2425< /GmapID><Name>Anna Thomsen (Anniplaze)<//Name>< user>
112512975718705609662</user>
<pics>None< /pics>< Review>
The only reason why I didn't give them 5 stars was because of the medical bill in the end and how expensive it was, but that is to be expected when it's at 3:30am on a Sunday. I wish there were urgent cares a little cheaper for when emergencies arrive, but that's a different story.
When I first called them at around 2am with the issue going on, they were really kind and professional and they were doing all they could to help me take care of this issue from home so I could avoid the expense of bringing my kitten in. They told me what to look out for and if the situation continued then bring her in. I was really grateful for them and how considerate they were. When it did come down to me having to bring my cat in, they were very prompt in bringing her in (even with COVID-19's safety procedures putting a wrench in it all by not allowing me to go inside) and I got a phone call from a tech or the doctor herself about every 20 minutes with updates on how my kitten was doing and what they were doing. They always called with an estimate before they did something, which is another thing I was really grateful for, too. It came down to that we didn't really have an explanation for what was going on and the doctor again told me that she 1) felt the kitten was stable enough to go home so we wouldn't have to hospitalize her and 2) would give me stuff to help my kitten at home with the vomiting. Although she couldn't promise me that this situation wouldn't continue, she told me she was confident that the kitten would recover on her own, but if she didn't, to bring her back in (and she gave me a list of symptoms to watch out for again).
Very kind, considerate and professional staff. Although I pray we never have to go back because of the price (and who ever wants their pet to get sick or hurt??), I trust their staff and this animal hospital for any emergencies that may arise with my pets!< /Review>

< userid>
113288213899936355171</userid>
<Name>1988remixx< /Name>< Time>
1604852872511</Time>
<rating>4</rating>< review>
We have a 5 month old puppy & he's like a vacuum, picking up & eating anything he see's when we go out on walks. He had the typical signs of eating something bad vomiting, lethargy etc & it obviously was not agreeing with him or obstructing his bowels.

This was the closest 24hr Urgent Care in South OC to where we live in Lake Forest. I will have to stay their procedure during the COVID situation is very good. You walk up to the front door, call that you've arrived, you fill out paper work outside, leave it on the table, everyone is face masked, they come & pick your pet up, you sit in your car or outside until they call you for results. So they get a 5 star for that.

The Vet is very thorough about going over her thoughts & opinions on what is going on with your pet & offers of course her suggestions which are NOT CHEAP! I'm used to Vet "up-selling" services to pad the price as much as possible, I get it, it's still a business, they know many are going to deny certain services so just be aware to READ over the price list of everything that WAS done & everything they want to do.

In the end it took about 3hrs & we didn't come home until midnight. This was a very expensive trip to the Vet to basically state, "He ate something off the ground & he has a tummy ache"!! Uhggggg! But how are we to know this up front & we're grateful of this type of service for at very least it can give you some reassurance that you did right by your pet.< /review>

I am very impressed with Animal Urgent Care of South Orange County. I rushed my dog in after she had a seizure late in the evening. I was a complete mess and the staff was very warm and friendly. I had a short wait, as it is first come first serve but they took my dog back so they could observe her until there was an available vet. The lobby was very clean and comforting with lots of snacks, drinks, comfortable seating and it was decorated for Christmas. The doctor I spoke with was incredible intelligent, well educated and I was very grateful to have such a passionate vet to examine my pet. Everyone was just amazing, it was the best experience I could have had given the circumstances.

I am sure and hope it is case by case, but the first come, first serve method was a little distressing for me. I offered for several other people to go ahead of me, as my dog was in a fine state and just needed to be observed at this point but they said they operate 'first come, first serve". So hopefully if an animal is in more medical need, they will assist accordingly.<//Text>

< Review>
This is my experience dealing with Animal Urgent Care of South Orange County. Medical Negligence. Read the bottom to know your rights when your vet is medically negligent and harms your pet.

11/21: Our dog Tyson went in for blockage and GI surgery because he was throwing up his food and water - he needed immediate surgery. He had received several x-rays of both his chest and stomach and an ultrasound at his regular vets which confirmed the same. His chest was completely normal, no signs of irregularity or cancer. He never had signs of any chest issues. We were specifically dealing with stomach problems. Dr. Henry performed the surgery that night. She called us at 5am the next morning to let us know Tyson was awake. We arrived at the urgent care as soon as it opened to pick Tyson up and take him to his regular vet for follow up treatment. We waited in the waiting room as all the other animals were getting picked up. We also saw a dog rushed in that was attacked by a coyote. But still, we waited over an hour. The ladies at the front desk told us the doctor needed to speak with us directly. We had a bad feeling about it. We went into one of the rooms where we were met by Dr. Henry. She told us his surgery went well, his heart rate is normal, he did give them a struggle with the anesthesia, but other than that it went well. She handed us the ziplock bag of the blockage material Tyson had eaten. She told us they took biopsies and she did notice that Tyson had inflamed intestines (which was also indicated by our vet through X-ray, bariome radiography, and ultrasound prior to coming to urgent care). And then came the real kicker; At the end of his surgery when someone removed the tube that was going down into his stomach, they "forgot to suction out the brown GI fluid" before pulling it out, which slid back into his body, while under anesthesia, and right into his lungs. She made it seem like it wasn't a big deal. Then, when we saw Tyson, we could hear the cackling noises as he struggled to breathe. He coughed the entire car ride to his vet for post-op treatment.
(See photos for full story)

Tyson is continuing to throw up because he needs the prednisone to treat the inflamed intestines, but the prednisone will worsen the pneumonia. The pneumonia has prevented Tyson from receiving the care he actually needs. This is directly the fault of Animal Urgent Care of South Orange County.

All pet owners have rights. Please be aware of them. Martinez v. Robledo (2012) held that when a veterinary hospital is medically negligent, the owner can recover the reasonable cost of care endured as a result of that negligence. Pets are not valuable on their own except to their owners, and are therefor entitled not only to the value of their pet, but also to the costs endured. Tyson is our fur baby, a part of our family, and has had to endure suffering for more than two weeks because of their negligence. This urgent care isn't taking responsibility for their actions. Be careful if you decide to come here.

Edit: Tyson passed away 3 weeks ago as a result of this negligence. The manager has responded to us through yelp. I haven‚Äôt had the strength to face his loss, let alone respond to her. I will be sending her a package with all of his medical bills for his post op care relating to their negligence with the hopes they will do the right thing. This Christmas has been difficult, and has felt empty without him. Tyson was my world. Some people have kids, I had Tyson.< /Review>

It was a very traumatic time for us and it was great to know my "babies" were in such good hands.  In this time of my personal disaster, it was nice to have professional, calm people helping me.  I am so grateful that you are here to help the people and pets of South Orange County and only wish we had a "human" 24 hour care who was similar to your expertise and affordability.

Everything was up front and told in advance of what the charges would be; not like going to the ER at our local San Clemente Hospital.  They see you for a few minutes and send - not one but several - shockingly outrageous overcharged bills later.  You were very detailed on your fees and gave options for services performed.

This is an extremely well performing company with a highly trained Staff who truly care about the people and pets that they serve.  It's nice to see when a business is run as it should; and we are lucky to have this Animal Urgent Care facility available.  Thank you to one and all who helped my girls; Lexy and Gypsy that night.  Thank you from the bottom of my heart!<//Text>

<user>113583421752797491910<//user>< Name>
Jacqueline Coughlin<//Name>
<date>1383241120346< /date><Rate>4</Rate>< Text>
My dog woke me up in the middle of the night in hives.  I took him to Animal Urgent Care right away.  I walked in the door and didn't even have to sit down and wait, was immediately brought into an exam room.  The vet tech came in within minutes and the vet was in in under 5 minutes.

My dog was very scared and not too thrilled to have people looking at and touching him, but the vet was very kind and knew how to make my dog feel more comfortable and that she was someone he could trust.

He ended up getting a shot of a steroid to help the hives and bring down the swelling.  I was told to wait for 30-45 minutes to see how the shot worked.  After 45 minutes my dog still had a few hives and some swelling so they offered me a few options.  I could either go home and leave my dog for observation, stay an hour longer to see if he got better, or take more of the steroid and go home.  I mentioned that if possible I didn't want to pay more than needed, so they ended up giving more of the steroid for no additional charge.  We went home and the next morning my dog was as good as new.

I really appreciate the rapid service and compassion by all the staff.  It puts me at ease knowing we have a ER vet so close to us in times of need.  Pets are family and deserve the best!<//Text>

< Text>
After my girlfriend picked up a puppy out of the street that had been hit by a car and likely had a broken leg or pelvis, MV animal control asked us to take the dog here. When we dropped the dog off we left a phone number and asked them to please contact us if the owners were not found as we would gladly pay for any surgery that was needed.

Several days later I saw the puppy on the lost and found website. A couple days after that it was removed. I hoped that meant they had found the owners. Well I found out from a friend that worked at a different animal hospital that they took the dog to my friends hospital and had the puppy put to sleep. Outraged I emailed them and got a response that "it would have cost thousands to fix his broken leg". To which I replied that I said I would have GLADLY paid that and that my girlfriend who also works at an animal hospital could have had the leg amputated- worst case scenario- for less than one thousand dollars.

Do NOT take any animal here if you want to be sure it isn't killed. I am appalled at this place and hope people hear my outrage and avoid them at all costs. I have never been so infuriated and disgusted with a bunch of people who "care about animals" so much in my life. Wish I could give them negative stars, Please stay away from this place.<//Text>

< review>
I have had Boxer dogs for over 20 years and have dealt with illnesses, injuries and the ache of losing my babies.  Just today, I had to send my last two Boxers into God's hands.

Dr. Silvia arrived on time and was immediately compassionate and supportive to the tremendous pain I was feeling.  She and her technician were gentle, professional, caring, compassionate, and soothing.  I took my dogs to Three Dogs Bakery for some yummy cookies and treats, took them to the beach to enjoy the ocean breeze on their faces and the surf on their paws, then brought them home and the three of us laid on the grass in the front yard until it was time to go.

It will be some time before my heart recovers but I am glad beyond words that I was able to take care of my sweet, loving dogs by making their last breath one of comfort, laying in the sun with a gentle breeze.  Thank you Dr. Silvia for making a tremendously painful experience in my life more bearable.

K. Russell
San Clemente, CA<//review>

<userid>113790101439522665435</userid><name>J.D. Calzada< /name>< time>
1383267140169<//time>
<rating>5< /rating>< review>
On a Sunday evening, I took my 18 year old kitty, Seal, in for an inordinate amount of blood in her urine. It was done out of character on my floor instead of the little box. I knew she needed care post haste.

Facility and Care:

As a pet industry professional and pet steward, I have high standards. In the past, I have walked out of modern, well rated facilities in favor of the downtown strip mall where I know the vet is good and the staff caring. As a careful observer I did take note: it was clean, the vet on duty was kind and understanding (even when I had "mom panic"), and the vet techs were alert and informative.

In my experience, a good vet tech that interacts professionally with both you and your pet is as important as a good vet. They are the ones that monitor your pets vitals, deliver medicine, and have the schlep job of making sure a facility full of equipment and sick, unpredictable animals is safe for your little fuzzbuckets. These guys handled my little girl (and my blubbering, tearful concerns) with efficiency and a smile.

Price:

I feel I was charged fairly for the services and my cat is healthier now after a follow up with my regular vet.

I realize there are industry price differences. I did not get surgery, tests, or any of the usual costly things. I only want to point out that running a facility of this nature here in Orange County is costly, think supplies and space. The techs went to school. They have hard, physical days and emotionally demanding shifts. The Vet went to school, often longer than you and at great expense. They are a business. Because you found it way cheaper online, at clinic, or in the next city over...doesn't mean the facility should eat the difference.

I have had, won, and lost many battles with the medical care of animals. Poor reviews are valued and often warranted for caution, but they are also sometimes written in anger and grief over loss of a loved one (blame has to go somewhere, right?). Or they are over money. The first I can identify with, I take those with a grain of salty tears. The latter I find subject to varied degrees of perception and without the whole story, I can't judge. So I don't. The 18 years of companionship from my cat doesn't have a price tag, whether I am hungry and unemployed or simply surviving in Orange County.< /review>

<name>Julie Palmer<//name>< rate>
5</rate>
<date>1376079766010< /date>< review>
I cannot say enough to praise Dr. Diehl and the staff of the Animal Urgent Care. We brought our cat here after finding him in very serious condition. Dr. Diehl reviewed her findings and preliminary thoughts on the diagnosis very thoroughly and presented several treatment options for us to consider. Our cat was FIV+ and in serious condition; the chances were very likely that he was battling cancer that he would have extremely low chances of surviving, so we ultimately made the decision to put our friend to rest. We were given as much time as we needed to spend with our furry friend before putting him to sleep and all of the staff was extremely supportive. Dr. Diehl asked if we wanted her to do an autopsy to determine if it was indeed cancer, but we opted not to since we had already made the decision and didn't want to feel guilty if he did not have cancer and find that we had said goodbye too soon. She ended up leaving us a message on our drive home saying that she understood our concerns about the autopsy but wanted us to know that the blood work did confirm that our friend had cancer. It was such a kind, thoughtful gesture that brought us so much peace and relief to know that we had done what was best. This was such an amazing display of compassion that we will never forget. If you ever find yourself in urgent need of care for your pets, I highly recommend the Animal Urgent Care of South Orange County without hesitation.<//review>

ben valdez<//name>
<Date>1400021673423< /Date>< Rate>
5< /Rate>
<text>Needless to say, we were highly concerned when we woke one Sunday morning to find that our Siberian husky Tasha had been vomiting and exhibiting bloody diarrhea several times overnight. We were in a cabin 100 miles from our home in southern Orange County, and we knew this was serious because of the potential for severe dehydration so we drove directly to the Animal Urgent Care.
When we arrived, Dr. Diehl, the veterinarian on duty, examined Tasha immediately and tentatively diagnosed her condition as HGE. She put Tash on an IV drip to re-hydrate her and administer medication, and ordered a number of relevant tests, which they were able to perform on site. We left her at the hospital overnight and we were worried that because Tash has acute separation anxiety and especially detests crates and kennels, we thought leaving her overnight might cause her additional stress. Dr. Diehl called us a few hours later with an update on her condition and the results of the tests they had performed. She also told us that in addition to administering a mild sedative, one of the staff was sitting by Tash whenever she was awake to help keep her calm.
Tash looked much improved the next morning when we picked her up to take her to her regular vet, and one week later she seems very nearly back to normal.
All the staff at the urgent care facility were very professional and responsive. In particular, Dr. Diehl's "bedside manner" was superb with both Tasha and her worried humans. We are very fortunate to have such a superb urgent care capability so close to home.</text><pics>None</pics>< Resp>

<Name>Mark Lovett< /Name><gmapID>0x80dcee896354092b:0x1569bc95125a2425</gmapID>< text>
I recently took my dog to Animal Urgent Care. My dog was throwing up for 3 days and was really dehydrated. Upon the doctors initial inspection she noted that the dog is in fact dehydrated and would need to stay for 12 hrs to be rehydrated. She said she would need to run some tests to see what the problem was. Total cost was around $1800. I said that I couldn't afford this much so she took some stuff out. After the doctor ran a panel on the dog showed that all blood counts don't match up. I paid $230-$275 for the panel. The panel of course showed that she is dehydrated of course! So I made the decision to keep the dog overnight for $1,300 to stay alive and get rehydrated. At 3am another doctor called me to let me know the dog is still vomiting and she would need to run an ex ray for $280 or so. I went forward with it and they found nothing. She said then they need to do an ultrasound to determine if there is a foreign body found cost $290. She then proceeded to tell me if they did find something in the stomach blocking then the dog would need surgery which would run around $3,200 or more. I said I am already into this around $1900 and cannot afford much more. The new doctor came in at 7am who originally diagnosed my dog, she mentioned the costs again. I stated that unfortunately I would have to relinquish my dog to a charity or put the dog down due to financial hardship. They said give us a minute and we will call you back. They said the doctor has been calling around other vets in the area and found a surgeon in Yorba Linda that would complete the surgery and post op for $1800. So I took my pet and completed the surgery at Yorbalinda pet hospital and they found a palm seed in the stomach.
All in all I found them to be very patient and nice however a lot of upselling if I was willing to pay for it. They should just offer to open the dog up for exploratory surgery rather than paying $2,200 or much more to diagnose. I would not bring my pet back again unless I had pet insurance and they paid for the upcharges and hard sell. I will call the doctor at Yorba Linda next time even though it is 30 min. from my house.<//text>

This establishment amazed me from the moment I walked in to the moment I walked out.
My first thought was it looked and felt like a 5 star day spa. In my experience when a business puts this much in to the appearance of the place then the service provided and the skill sets of the employees fall short... but not here. 5 stars from start to finish.
Not only was the staff super friendly and helpful, but the technology they had was beyond anything I have ever heard of or seen. There was a massage chair in a room that I was able to use prior to my appointment, and a 3D picture machine that allowed us to see what my teeth looked like at every angle, where I put the most pressure when biting down, and what my teeth could look like if I were to get Invisalign. Jen was the Hygenist that cleaned my teeth. She was out of this world and took her time explaining everything she was seeing and doing. Dr. Thomas was super thorough and helped me map out my dental future.
I have never enjoyed going to the dentist until now. My teeth feel super clean, and I‚Äôm moving forward with a better smile in the near future.
Highly recommend!<//text>

I found them through my insurance company‚Äôs website. After a year of pandemic and moving cross country, it‚Äôs been a while since my last dental visit. A few hours before my appointment, I was informed that the dental hygienist was ill. There wasn‚Äôt an offer to reschedule, but because of my work demands, I really wish they had because it‚Äôs difficult for me to arrange coverage to go in yet another time for care I expected this appointment.They said I should feel free to come in earlier but because of my work requirements, I could not, so what may have seemed like a nice offer came across as not understanding the demands of my job. Upon arriving, I found it strange that they had three receptionists but apparently only one dental hygienist. The receptionist took my temperature, mentioned she should take it again because it was low at 96? Said she would ten minutes later but never did. She  offered me a cold beverage including  Izzes, which I found strange for a place that‚Äôs passionate about dentistry since those are high in sugar. I would have liked to have been informed earlier that my earlobe piercings would have affected the X-ray and had to spend a long time removing them because they were small and secured. I would‚Äôve removed them before the appointment had I known. Unlike typical experiences, they put your X-rays, pictures, and scans up front of which I am now realizing might be a ploy to shame you into thinking your teeth are not cosmetically appealing so you‚Äôll be more willing to buy their procedures. At first I thought it was cool, but after my pictures, I started feeling ashamed of my teeth and became nervous. The assistant complimented my dress but then said it reminded her of Fall, which maybe she thought was nice but when I mentioned the comment to a friend, she couldn‚Äôt get over how backhanded that seemed, like I‚Äôm wearing something from last season. Assistant said I had small teeth. Ok. What am I supposed to do with that? She commented that I had some plaque buildup, and it was a shame the hygienist had a migraine. I was thinking ‚ÄúI know.‚Äù  Dr. Thomas was thorough in her exam, but I get the feeling that there is a weird cross between a ‚Äúpassion‚Äù for dental health and up selling. I‚Äôve had braces but admit some things have shifted a bit since the 23 years they have been off.When I mentioned I wasn‚Äôt interested in Invisalign, the conversation switched from cosmetically fixing my crowding to bite placement fracturing and chipping my teeth if I don‚Äôt get it corrected. Back at reception, they told me the date and time of when I would come in for my rescheduled cleaning, which would not work with my schedule. I was surprised they didn‚Äôt talk to me first about what would work. Again, not caring about the demands of my job. I will be getting a cleaning over a month from now. And then the receptionist called me by the wrong name. At first I thought she was talking to someone else, so I didn‚Äôt think anything of it, but when she wrote ‚ÄúAmanda‚Äù on my appointment card, I realized the mistake. It didn‚Äôt leave me feeling like my medical information was secure or that anyone really cared about me. Dr. Thomas will respond to this review with a somewhat canned response about passion and trust (or maybe with some vague details that skirt a HIPAA violation?), but here I am doubting if I can trust anyone. I cried when I got home because I wasn‚Äôt self conscious about my teeth‚Äôs appearance before‚Äîhave even thought my smile was my best feature , and now I‚Äôm worried that they‚Äôre small, crowded, stained, and ugly. I‚Äôm crying because I‚Äôm not sure if the passion is because  Dr. Thomas cares or if it‚Äôs just about the money. No one should feel confused or worse after a routine exam, and I‚Äôm worried this is the future of dentistry‚Äîproducts over people. But their reception area has wrap around couches, elaborate fountains, and some Buddha art.< /text>

< Review>
Reflections has amazing reviews and I hate to be one of the few people that leaves a negative review. However with everything that is going on right now I feel like people should speak up and always try to be as fair as we can. So here is my review.

I visited Reflections for the first time yesterday as a new patient with the intention to get a teeth cleaning and a start a new dentist relationship since I recently moved to the area. When I walked in I noticed a clean office and a friendly front office staff. The lady on the front desk handed me a tablet to fill in the initial patient intake form. Everything was pretty straight forward at that point.

I was then passed to the back where a very friendly dental assistant took my X-Rays and started the initial evaluation of my teeth. I have moved quite a bit so I knew that this was standard procedure when you go to a new dental office. However my intention on this first visit was still having a  regular cleaning and see what else was going on with my dental hygiene. The dental technician was friendly and thorough. After her initial evaluation the  dentist came in and started her own evaluation. This is when I started to get the feeling that something was off. Everything about the way she was talking felt like if someone was just making a list of all the services that she was going to charge you for. I listened to all her remarks. At the end of her evaluation I asked yet again if a cleaning was now coming. She just said ... Ohh dont worry someone will come in and tell you all we can do for you ... so you can do as much as you want until 5pm when we leave.

After that the lady on the front office came in with a tablet with a long menu of procedures ... her attitude at this point was not so much friendly but nervous as if this part of the job is uncomfortable. She started trying to explain all the items on her list and she noticed  that I was not comfortable at this point she tried to rush the explanation and just went directly to the bottom line which was 3000 plus dollars and I guess the awesome part was that my insurance would cover half of it. When I pointed to her that for me paying 1000 plus dollars in the economic environment we are all in know might not be feasible. She just told me that maybe we got off to the wrong foot and we would not be a good fit. When I responded that all I wanted for that day was to get a teeth cleaning she said that they are not the type of office that a patient can come in and dictate what they want to the doctor and that given my situation a teeth cleaning would be detrimental to my situation.

That is exactly when I decided to write this post. How can a teeth cleaning be detrimental ... I might as well not brush my teeth if I dont get all these procedures done first .. I guess I dont know ...

Is MY personal experience that this office cares much more about selling than the patient.

Jorge< /Review>

<Rating>1</Rating>< review>
I want to start by saying the actual dentists here are great,  I have no problems with Dr Thomas or Dr Masters.  However, the front desk and billing team can make or break a practice and unfortunately this one is breaking it.  We have been going here for 2 years.  Every single bill has an error.  Every single one.  Charged for fluoride that didn't happen, insurance adjustments not made, etc.  every appointment they are pushing to get more money and feels like all they care about is money.  I've been told multiple times by Veronica that my dental insurance "pays soooo low" and is terrible.  Then why are you in network with it?  Then this week I get notices that they have tried billing my health insurance for X-rays that my dental insurance already paid for.  Why would you be double billing for the same thing?  Last straw was on Tuesday of this week when I called with a dental emergency and was told bc of COVID,  I couldn't be seen for 2 weeks.  For a dental emergency, his tooth broke in half and nerves exposed! Then when i called the office for clarification Veronica told me it was my fault for not clearly explaining it was an emergency bc they are seeing patients for emergencies... what more does i need to say than emergency to get the point across?  The front desk obviously wasn't trained on how to respond to emergency calls.  But rather than taking ownership of that, she blames me.  I don't know if the dentists are aware of how terrible the front desk is treating their patients.  Bc as a small business owne, I know the customers come first and the dentist most likely wouldn't want 3 patients being lost bc of the front desks attitude.  Do not waste your time here.< /review>

<resp>None< /resp>< review>
I've been wanting to try this place for a while as some friends had told me it was really good and the rating looked good. I was not disappointed in the food! Their food is really good and everyone in our group enjoyed what they ordered. I had a late lunch and a sore tooth so I wasn't very hungry and ordered the baba ganoush wrap because I thought it would be soft and not very filling. The flavor was fantastic! I tried my friend's side dish of spicy potatoes and loved it. The only downside to this place is the staff doesn't really seem to know what they're doing. Maybe because it's a fairly new place things aren't in order yet, but they made mistakes with a couple of my friends orders and they were SO SLOW. I'm disabled and standing is extremely difficult for me and I probably stood there for 10 minutes waiting to have my order taken and then having someone ring it up. They even had problems with the cash register. I'll give them another shot when they've ironed out the kinks as their food is delicious, priced well & is close to my house. They also have a nice variety of grocery items, desserts & frozen yoghurt.</review>
